description:
Pickleball is rapidly growing in popularity across Vietnam, especially in Hanoi.
Dozens of new courts operate from before sunrise until after midnight.
The sport’s accessibility, light paddles, and entertaining rules attract all ages.
Courts are often squeezed into alleyways and beneath high-rises in densely packed cities.
However, residents complain about relentless noise, citing disrupted sleep and concentration.
Experts warn that the high-pitched sounds may increase stress and cardiovascular risks.
Authorities face a dilemma as an estimated 16 million people play while noise complaints rise.

Al Jazeera’s Joanna Gasiorowska reports.

description:
Taiwan sits between the East and South China seas, central to the global economy despite its small size.
At Keelung fishing harbour, crews face uncertainty as Chinese military drills threaten local waters.
Many workers, including migrants from China, value Taiwan’s better jobs and stability but worry about rising tensions.
Keelung port is a vital hub for trade, security, and the global supply chain, handling cargo, cruise liners, and coastguard patrols.
Taiwan produces most of the world’s smartphone and computer chips, making any conflict potentially devastating for the global economy.
Local markets and small businesses, from fishmongers to bubble tea vendors, already feel the impact of political pressures.
A takeover of Taiwan would reshape borders, society, and its global economic influence.

Al Jazeera’s Zein Basravi reports from Keelung port in northern Taiwan.

description:
Displaced families in Sudan’s White Nile State are facing a growing health emergency.
Ongoing war and tribal unrest have cut off access to food, clean water and healthcare.
Thousands are forced to rely on untreated water from the White Nile River.
As a result, water-borne diseases are spreading rapidly in displacement camps.
Young children are dying from bilharzia, a preventable parasitic disease.
Aid shortages and insecurity are worsening conditions for already vulnerable families.
Residents fear the crisis will deepen without urgent humanitarian intervention.

Al Jazeera’s Mohammed Vall reports from Kosti, Sudan.

author: Al Jazeera English
description:
Senior Syrian and Israeli officials are holding a second day of US-brokered talks in Paris as tensions rise along the Syria–Israel frontier. 
Central to discussions is the 1974 Disengagement Agreement, which froze front lines, set a UN buffer zone, and limited forces on both sides for decades. 
Recent Israeli advances into southern Syria, including parts of the buffer zone, have Damascus calling violations of the accord. 
In Beit Jin in southern Syria, residents report increasingly aggressive incursions near civilian homes, breaking the long-standing tense status quo. 
Washington aims to contain conflict and limit regional spillover, while Israel seeks greater control and leverage, and Syria insists on full sovereignty and a return to the 1974 terms. 
The outcome of these talks could determine whether the border maintains uneasy restraint or escalates into wider conflict.

Al Jazeera’s Resul Serdar reports from Beit Jin in southern Syria.

title: Syria and Israel hold second day of US-brokered Paris talks as border tensions rise
